sample.title: How subsea cables power the global internet
sample.description:
Over 95% of international data and voice call traffic travels through nearly a million miles of underwater communication cables.

These cables carry government communications, financial transactions, email, video calls and streaming around the world.

Demand for subsea cables is increasing as tech giants race to develop computation-intensive artificial intelligence models and connect their growing networks of data centers.

sample.title: How AI Is Killing The Value Of A College Degree
sample.description:
Youth unemployment in the U.S. is rising. For 16-to-24-year-olds, the unemployment rate jumped from 6.6% in April 2023, the lowest since the pandemic, to 10.4% in September, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. Recent college graduates are particularly struggling to find jobs, prompting economists at The Burning Glass Institute to describe the situation as ‚Äúno country for young grads.‚Äù Watch the video to find out why these young minds are not landing jobs, whether AI plays a role, and what this means for the economy.

sample.title: How AI Layoffs Could Backfire On Employers
sample.description:
Generative AI is speeding up how people work, but that efficiency can prevent some workers from climbing the corporate ladder. Nearly 40% of workers‚Äô core skills will be disrupted by 2030 due to AI and digitalization, according to the World Economic Forum. It may become more difficult for entry-level workers to advance in their careers as companies cut costs by trimming middle management and, in certain industries, eliminate entry level roles that can be replaced by AI. Watch this video to understand the impending break down between the expert and novice educational relationship and what that means for the future of the economy.

sample.title: China launches spaceship to bring stuck astronauts back home | BBC News
sample.description:
China has launched a spacecraft to allow them to bring back three astronauts, stuck in the country's space station, back to earth. 
 
The unmanned Shenzhou-22 was not supposed to be launched until April next year.
 
But the crew on the space station currently have no way of returning home if there was an emergency because an earlier launch vehicle was declared unfit to fly after its window was cracked by suspected space debris.

sample.description:

A rescue operation is under way for the 253 children and 12 teachers who remain missing.
